<p>The <tt>lea</tt> (load effective address) instruction is used to put a memory address into the destination.
</p>
<h1><span class="mw-headline" id="Syntax">Syntax</span></h1>
<pre>lea <i>destination</i>, <i>source</i>
</pre>
<h1><span class="mw-headline" id="Examples">Examples</span></h1>
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td>
<dl><dt><tt>lea eax, [ebx+8]</tt></dt>
<dd>Put <tt>[ebx+8]</tt> into <tt>EAX</tt>. After this instruction, <tt>EAX</tt> will equal <tt>0x00403A48</tt>.</dd></dl>
<div style="margin:5px; padding:5px; border-left: solid 10px #90C3D4; background:#E9F2F5;">
<div style="margin:3px;font-weight:bold;">Note</div>
<div>In contrast, the instruction <tt>mov eax, [ebx+8]</tt> will make <tt>EAX</tt> equal to <tt>0x0012C140</tt></div>